(1 comment)

This change is ready for review.
Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 0688132a438d5d9596184b15b1e105f70bd47b4e
why not obmc-chassis-powercycle@{}.target instead of obmc-chassis-powerreset@{}.target

Because the target file in the "phosphor-state-manager" recipe is named "obmc-chassis-powerreset@target", but the chassis transition property defined in the "phosphor-dbus-interface" recipe is "PowerCycle".

Did you think we should change the name to "obmc-chassis-powercycle@{}.target", including the target filename?
yes, if possible you could change both the places.

The "obmc-chassis-powerreset@.target" is actually for a different function. It handles detecting if chassis power is on after a BMC reset and if it is on, it creates the /run/openbmc/chassis@%i-on file to indicate chassis power is already on after a BMC reboot.

I recommend you create a new target for this function, obmc-chassis-powercycle@{}.target. At a high level this new target should call obmc-chassis-hard-poweroff@.target and then obmc-chassis-poweron@.target (or maybe obmc-host-start@.target if it wants to fully boot the system?)

One issue we had with the host-reboot path is that systemd does not handle well having 2 conflicting targets in the same target (i.e. chassis-off/on). I had to introduce a service, phosphor-reboot-host@.service that works around this systemd limitation. Something similar may be needed here for this powercycle target.

Thanks. We will add default power cycle target and check target conflict issue in chassis-powercycle. 

Change status to wip.

Some commit message nuances. The "Summary" is your first line. The expectation is that this section of the commit message is where you explain why this commit is needed. So remove the "Summary" and just add some text about why this commit is needed (i.e. A new system is being designed which will utilize phosphor-state-manager and it requires the chassis system power cycle feature).

We changed the commit message.
Thanks for reviewing.
I don't think you want this Conflicts. The "powercycle" will probably start this target under the covers (to power off) then call the power on target.

We removed the conflict setting.
Thanks for reviewing.
Please check your git-config on this as well.
Feel free to submit when you're ready.
